text:
The Matrix is a remake of Tron. A user is finding his way through the inner software of a computer. There are programs trying to stop him. That's Tron. Some of the effects are impressive, but some of the story is just dumb.
Using people as a source of electricity? Surely, just burning food in a steam engine will get more BTUs out of the food than the surplus a human body will provide.
Then, in the big showdown, they are using mechwarriors without face coverings for the pilots. Obvious what's going to result from that design flaw. Then, in the dumbest flaw of all, with all the sophisticated technology they have developed, when the mechs run out of bullets, they get reloaded from one kid running around with a wheelbarrow.
I'll never watch one minute of any Matrix sequel again. I'd vote for a Republican first.

text:
Great list, thanks for compiling!

Perhaps the list should be a bit longer? A top 40 or maybe 50? The original Invasion of The Body Snatchers was far better than the remake, just my opinion. The 1950s War of The Worlds will always belong in the top 10. 

Some of the following fantastic SF films may be unknown to younger viewers. I would suggest a longer list, just to be complete.

Predator, The Andromeda Strain, The Terminator, 12 Monkeys, Gattaca, The Thing, They Live, Lucy, Soylent Green, Stargate, The Fifth Element, Robocop, I saw Colossus: The Forbin Project at the Drive in - great SF, saw Alien at the theater with 2 other couples, I cannot overstate the shocked reaction of the entire audience, Charly, Destination Moon, The Edge of Tomorrow ( just a great SF film), The Brit Peter Cushing version of 1984 - best rendition of the book, Rod Taylor version The Time Machine, Fahrenheit 451, I am sure others will come up with more..

Many Honorable Mentions, 5 Million Years To Earth, Battle Los Angeles, Oblivion, Paycheck,  Things to Come, The Incredible Shrinking Man, James Mason versions 20,000 Leagues Under The Sea and Journey to The Center  of The Earth, Gravity - Sandra Bullock, Coneheads, Demolition Man

text: Almost all Science Fiction (SF) is Social Science Fiction (SSF) like The Hunger Games, or 1984. The Wrath of Kahn like most of Star Trek is Space Opera. I'm starting to doubt this ranking because Solaris is too good for this list. 17 & 16 are SSF.  I need to see 15 again - undecided. Didn't like 14 too much. The whole series was really depressing. So were the 70s. 13 was good. Was never a big fan of 12. Regarding 11 - it's like you are supposed to like it because it's such a slick movie. Well ok I guess.  Was never a fan of #10 - too old I guess. Number 9 is a real classic, and for me is real SF. Amazing. Number 8 - more SSF. Number 7 - a classic again. Number 6 - I agree, and another huge classic.  No 5. Other people way before me said "Star Wars is not Science Fiction. So it's really SSF - but great of course. No 4. oh yes. more great SSF. Same with #3 especially considering that "copper top" concept would never work. Not sure #2 belongs on this list OR at least not ranked at #2. Can't argue about #1.

text:
Without watching the video first I'd say: BULLSHEIT! :D
First off, notes to the list "Top 20 Greatest Sci-Fi Movies of All Time":
Avatar - including that movie to the list is an insult for the genre, the MOVIE is not good, the new technology used sure as hell is phenomenal but fancy effects do not make a good movie
Mad Max: Fury Road - seriously, you pick the shittiest film of the franchise that has no story and no Mad Max? pfff

I understand that this list is a "personal" choice and does not reflect back on the actual genre and this said by now there are far to many awsome SciFi movies to point out just "Greatest Sci-Fi Movies of All Time", especially if the list contains mostly movies from the last two decades! But the list was surprisingly good overall. But still for a Greatest Sci-Fi Movies of All Time list ...

text: From the perspective of someone who saw ESB when it first came out, when I was a ten-year-old boy:  That reveal was devastating, emotional, incredible.  My eyes were wide as saucers in the theater.  I refused to believe it.  My friends and I all debated, Was Darth Vader telling the truth?  That was part of what made ROTJ such a huge hit.  Not just all the robots and alien creatures in Jabba's palace that they made toys of and the rescue of Han Solo.  Not just the final battle.  Not just the lovable Ewoks (I'm kidding about the Ewoks.  We thought they were lame.  Didn't stop us from buying the action figures though).  It was that we finally got the truth, confirmed by Yoda and Obi-Wan.  Luke was going to have to go up against his own father to win.  Boy, did Lucas know how to keep his audience invested back then.  How things have changed.

text: Had to agree with most of your picks, but one of my all time favourites was Dark Star [1974] with John Carpenter producing and directing and Dan O'Bannon co-writing the film. Starting it's life as a  USC student film, it made it's way to limited theatrical release in 1974, debuting one of Hollywood's iconic directors in his career and ultimately becoming a cult classic.  Additionally, without the stupendously successful release of Star Wars IV: A New Hope [SW IV] in 1977, it's doubtful that anything in that franchise would have been made. For that alone, it ought to be included, but as with Avatar, SW IV introduced audiences to new CGI technologies, establishing an entirely new approach in the industry with the incorporation of Industrial Light and Magic.  Arguable that even Star Trek: The Motion Picture [1979] and it's follow-on films in that franchise would not have occurred without the impetus given to the industry by SW IV.  I will never forget the awe and stunned feelings I had as Darth Vader in that Star Cruiser chased after Princess Leia's ship in the opening sequence, and the jaw-dropping action sequences in the final battle against the Death Star. NOTHING like this had ever been done before. All succeeding films rest on the shoulders of this giant. Where would we be without CGI and green screen technology?

author: @peterwinters8587

text:
¬†@peterwinters8587¬† 2001: a Space oddysey is a deeper and more subtle film than Interstellar. It's also not about any love crap, it's a pure artistic beauty open for interpretation. The atmosphere, symbolism, artistry and influence are what makes 2001: a space oddysey the best sci-fi ever. Interstellar while good, was kinda pretentious and pushed all of it's science and depth down your throat, while 2001 : a space oddysey let watchers think on their own. 2001: a space oddysey might be the most groundbreaking film ever made - it completely changed the genre, the way people see space, It's effects and overall quality were far ahead of it's time that even movies made 20-30 years later look worse than it, It was accurate according to NASA, and was made before the moon landing.
Interstellar is only more entertaining if you expect a heartfelt story from a film, however If you watch movies as art form - 2001: a space oddysey would be a better option. As good as interstellar is, It's nowhere near being the best film of all time. There are many films that are simply superior

text: Listen, I can imagine that back in 1968 that 2001: A Space Odyssey was a mind-blowing, amazing, fantastic movie. There have been way more movies that have pushed the envelope and made us think way more constructively since this movie. This movie had over 40 minutes of SILENCE IN IT! The first words of dialogue aren't even spoken until 21 minutes in! I understand that dialogue isn't necessary for a movie to be great, but this movie is too slow of a burn and has entirely too many of these types of scenes in it. I have been hyped up about this my entire life and I watched it in 2021 and it was  tremendous letdown. Sorry, but 2001: A Space Odyssey is the most overrated, overhyped, over bloated science fiction movie I've seen so far.

text:
This list is a mess. 
-'Planet of the Apes' deserves a way higher number than a measly #14. 
-Although 'E.T: The Extraterrestrial' is a great movie, it's inclusion in the list should not have resulted in the exclusion of 'Jurassic Park', just because they are both Spielberg movie. That exclusion is itself a great crime against Sci-fi genre.
-I still don't understand the logic behind inclusion of 'Mad Max: Fury Road' under sci-fi genre till today. Just because a movie takes place in a dystopian future does not make it sci-fi. That movie is one of the best action/adventure movie, not a sci-fi movie. The same logic applies to 'Children of Men', except it's a n adventure/drama movie.
-If you are including 'The Invasion of Body Snatchers' in this genre, then 'The Thing' should also deserves an honorable mention.

Lots of good sci-fi movies ignored in this list makes me disappointed in WatchMojo.

text: I have always wondered why people in any way considered 2001: ASO vague or incomprehensible or hard to figure out. I didn't see it until I was 15 and it was released as the back half of a double feature when Logan's Run was released in 1976. At the time, Logan's Run was considered a bleeding edge SF film, but even then I considered 2001 VASTLY superior. The following year, STAR WARS recalibrated everyone's expectations. Think pieces fell out of favor, and SF wasn't considered marketable without high-speed chases, blaster fire, strange creatueea and spaceship battles. Still, 2001 walked so Solaris could run and films like Inception and Interstellar could fly.
